\begin_layout Section
Formation of four-magnon bound states
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In INS experiments on Fe
\begin_inset Formula $\text{I}_{2}$
\end_inset

, we observe a flat mode that is not reproduced by the SU(3) linear spin
 wave theory.
 The energy of that mode is approximately two times that of the two-magnon
 bound states (2MBS), therefore it should be a state made up of 
\series bold
two
\series default
 2MBS.
 Let's understand the formation of this state in real space: creating two
 2MBS on the nearest neighbor bond is energetically more favorable that
 creating them far apart, because the nearest neighbor bond of Fe
\begin_inset Formula $\text{I}_{2}$
\end_inset

 is ferromagnetic, which acts as an attractive potential to lower the energy
 of the two 2MBS.
 
\end_layout

